Message: 132 years ago on this date, back in 1884, Eleanor Roosevelt was born in NYC.
Description:
On this date, back in 1884, Eleanor Roosevelt was born in NYC. She was an American politician, diplomat, and activist. She was the longest-serving First Lady of the United States, having held the post from March 1933 to April 1945 during her husband President Franklin D. Roosevelt's four terms in office. She also served as United States Delegate to the United Nations General Assembly from 1945 to 1952.

President Harry S. Truman later called her the "First Lady of the World" in tribute to her human rights achievements.

In 1996 a sculpture of Eleanor was dedicated at 72nd Street & Riverside Dr. in the presence of Hillary Rodham Clinton, First Lady of the United States at the time.

Please share this moment in time. (Y) 5D GUIDE to connect NYC history with visuals and align it to the dates when events happened.

Message: 46 years ago today back in 1970 50,000 women marched down 5th Av. demanding equality.
Description:
Today back in 1970, 50 years after the passage of the 19th Amendment granting women the right to vote, 50,000 feminists paraded down New York City’s Fifth Avenue.

The event primarily focused on equal opportunity in the workforce, political rights for women, and social equality in relationships such as marriage. It also addressed the right to have an abortion and free childcare.

The event's leader was Betty Friedan, president of the National Organization for Women (NOW), an organization that aims to bring women "into the mainstream of American society in full and equal partnership with men."

Group Name: San Francisco Bay Area Street Photography
Message: Here are three press cameras from among the 20 or so that I’ll be displaying at next weekend’s Martinez Historic Home Tour. Our display will have fewer cameras than last year, but these are much larger cameras, and a very interesting collection that I’m proud to feature. It’s a very timely display as we head into the final stretch of this dramatic election year, and see the action though the eyes of the modern press cameras. My cameras displed below are the Kodak/Nikon DCS 420 from 1994, the Folmer & Schwing (Kodak) Speed Graphic from 1912, and the Mamiyaflex C2 from 1958. These were important press cameras in their times and each was a significant milestone in the evolution of press photography. These will be among my displayed cameras next weekend. Tickets are now available at: tinyurl.com/2016HT The Kodak DCS 420, circa 1994, was a Kodak digital “back” grafted onto a standard Nikon N90 film camera. At the time the N90 was arguably Nikon’s most advanced camera, with superior electronics to the flagship Nikon F4. For a photojournalist, the N90 offered reliable, fast, quality photos, and could use standard Nikon lenses. The DCS 420 cost between $15,000 and $20,000. The Associated Press was so impressed (truncated)

Description:
Vote yes on Question 2 for more money for public schools? How can that be?

Well, it's something like this. You have eight dollars and some change in your pocket, so you decide to get some lunch. You by a really yummy sandwich, but before you get a chance to eat, the neighborhood bully comes along and takes your lunch. Left with nothing more than some change in your pocket, you throw your last four quarters in the vending machine and buy a small bag of chips.

So, there you have it. You spent more money for lunch, nine dollars instead of eight dollars, but you certainly received a lot less than you started off with when the bully showed up.

It's the same thing for charter schools. With limited resources, school committees are squeezed between underfunded state appropriations and strict state limits on municipal taxation. A charter school is imposed by the state, and they take a very generous chunk out of your town's Chapter 70 aid. Maybe you can scrape up a couple of more bucks, some user fees, maybe an override, but you end up with much less than you started with for a higher cost.

Don't let a bunch of New York hedge fund guys eat your lunch. Vote NO on Question 2.

I've been receiving a smattering of e-mails from some of you purporting to support the Humann privatization plan for Fair Park. Here's the web form (strongly recommend you not use it):

http://www.fairpark.org/updates/20160826.html

And here's the email text it generates:

"Dear Council Member Philip Kingston,

I support the Fair Park Texas Foundation and urge you to vote in favor of this public, private partnership. We cannot waste the potential of this 277-acre Dallas treasure. I want to see more green space, year-round use and positive connections to the surrounding neighborhood. We need Foundation management and adequate funding. It is a time for Dallas to come together in support of action for Fair Park after years of disrepair." 

Here's what I've been sending back:

109 years ago on this date, back in 1907, the iconic Plaza Hotel opened in NYC.
Description:
On this date, back in 1907, the Plaza Hotel opened in New York.

The landmarked 20-story French Renaissance château-style building was designed by noted architect Henry J. Hardenbergh.

Many famous performers and guests have stayed at The Plaza. It has also been the meeting place for important political meetings. In 1993 Donald Trump celebrated his wedding to Marla Maples in front of 1,500 guests.

The building continues to serve as luxury hotel. In recent times some of the space was turned into condominium apartments. When the it opened, a room was only $2.50 per night, the equivalent of $63 today. The same room costs over 15 times as much today.

Please share this moment in time. (Y) 5D GUIDE to connect NYC history with visuals and align it to the dates when events happened.

Description:
Voters will face a decision this November regarding charter school caps – whether or not to authorize up to 12 new charter schools or expand enrollment in existing Massachusetts charter schools beginning as early as January 2017. Will a “yes” vote harm mainstream schools and undermine their funding? What other opportunities are there for parents stuck on charter school waiting lists? Will this decision influence the future of charter schools nationwide? This referendum has attracted national attention in the heated controversy about the future of charter schools in the U.S. public school education system. How do taxpayers/voters determine what’s best to keep mainstream school systems healthy while looking out for what’s best for individual children? Join us as proponents and opponents square off on the merits of charter school expansion in this inaugural of the Askwith Debates.

Participants:

Tito Jackson, District 7 city councilor and chairman, Committee on Education, Boston City Council
Marc Kenen, executive director, Massachusetts Charter Public School Association
Michael Robinson, former charter parent; current parent, Mansfield Public Schools; lead consultant, Collaborative Consulting
LaTasha Sarpy, (truncated)

Message: Also still fighting for the 22. How in any reality can they vote to destroy the 21, after they voted to preserve it as a state landmark?
Link Text: Preservation Action Council of San Jose
Description:
CENTURY 21 ALERT!!

Interested in having Century 21 restored and reused? The next step in the process is at Tuesday night's City Council meeting. The Council will discuss the proposed Santana West project sometime after the 7 PM meeting start time. Although final decisions won’t be made on the project at Tuesday’s meeting, the way things are going Tuesday’s decision will pretty much set the direction for what is going to happen in the future.

The actual decisions before the Council on Tuesday will be to certify the Santana West EIR and adopt a statement of overriding considerations and mitigation monitoring and reporting program; decisions related to the I-280/Winchester Boulevard Transportation Development Policy; approve a rezoning for the site to allow up to approximately one million square feet of office and commercial/retail, including mini-storage, outdoor theater, and television/radio station uses on an approximately 12.99 gross acre site.

The Mayor and some Council members have issued a memo (link below) approving the staff recommendations with some
modifications. Note Recommendation #9 which asks for "an analysis of the potential adaptive re-use of the Century 21 landmark
for a community-enhancing amenity beyond mere mini-storage use, such as a public plaza, open-air amphitheater, park or other
recreational use.”

It would appear the Mayor and some Council members are willing to at least consider a proposal that would destroy the historic integrity and status of the landmark Century 21 building. 

This meeting would be the time to voice your concerns if you think Century 21 should be restored and reused and not stripped away and turned into a shell. If you believe any proposal that basically strips the building apart and destroys its historic integrity should not receive any further consideration you should speak out Tuesday night.

Century 21 is a difficult building to reuse for something other than a theater. The movie business has changed since Century 21 was "the" place to see a movie in San Jose and the South Bay. If you don't believe that it's time has come and gone then this would be the time to share your ideas for viable proposals for reusing a restored Century 21, and not reducing it to a mere shell of the building. 

If the Mayor's recommendation moves forward there is a good chance that Century 21 may not survive.

In addition to speaking or commenting in writing at the City Council meeting, now would also be a good time to contact your Councilmember if you live in San Jose.

Below you will find links to the Mayor's memo and also the Supplemental Staff Report from the Planning Department.

http://sanjose.granicus.com/MetaViewer.php?view_id=&event_id=2154&meta_id=592472

http://sanjose.granicus.com/MetaViewer.php?view_id=&event_id=2154&meta_id=592642

Message: The agenda for next week's Orient Heights Neighborhood Council includes a vote pertaining to allowing a large billboard to be constructed on the property of the Hilton Garden Inn Hotel on Boardman Street. For those who have followed the saga of this proposal, you will remember that the Impact Advisory Group for the hotel's construction made it clear that there should be no high signage added to that area. At the time of the IAG's gatherings, there was agreement on that point between the residents and the development company. IMHO, it would signal diminution of the importance of IAGs in the community review process if those meetings were for naught. This would be the appropriate time for the city to implement a moratorium on any additional billboards within the city confines - starting with the McClellan Highway corridor. Due to my attending a wake and, then, attending to my son after an injury, I was unable to be present at the last two OHNC meetings, which means that I cannot vote at the upcoming meeting. May I respectfully request that others attend the meeting and, if eligible to do so, please vote against the Logan Communications proposal? Thank you. Marty Walsh, Salvatore LaMattina, Joe Boncore, Adrian Madaro, (truncated)

Message: Welcome to Texas: now time to register to vote! ***The deadline to register to vote is less than a month away (Oct. 11th) - you MUST be registered by Oct. 11th to vote in the November election.*** **Am I already registered?** Travis County - http://www.votetravis.com/vexpress/display.do Williamson County - http://apps.wilco.org/elections/default.aspx **How do I register to vote?** Travis County - Fill out a registration form here: https://tax-office.traviscountytx.gov/vo…/voter-registration Send it in through the mail(see form page) OR drop it off at any county tax office or a registration partner: https://tax-office.traviscountytx.gov/map Williamson County - Fill out form here: http://www.wilco.org/…/tab…/3674/language/en-US/Default.aspx Mail or drop it off at the location listed on the site above

“It didn't matter if you spoke the same language or not - you could really sense the community - the unity that we all had, the teamwork. It was pretty incredible … and really refreshing to see in these times right now.”

We’ll have it ready to go on KIRO 7 News at 6:10p. 
And please, share again!

I was flipping through photos this morning when it occurred to me that it's almost time for the annual WHC photo calendar competition! For those of you who know what I'm talking about, start getting your best shots ready as November is coming! For those of you who don't know, we run a contest each year for photos that are then printed into a WHC Calendar. Every member can submit one original photo and then the rest of the group uses "likes" to vote. The 14 photos with the most likes are then turned into a fabulous calendar by our fearless Lee-der and sent out to all of you. It's always tons of fun to see all of the talent in the group and the competition is fierce! Get your favorite shots ready or get out there and take some new ones! Submission and voting happens early- to mid-November! And, GO!

Message: This is very disappointing and should not be happening in our neighborhood meetings. I think it is important to address this. We should all be treated with respect and if we are disrespected, in the least the person should apologize. Without naming names, a leader of the Orient Heights Neighborhood Council at the last meeting said the following to a long-time member/advocate (who has done so much for this neighborhood) who just asked him this question in a calm and civil matter, "What are you going to do about the vote last month?" He responded with this, as far as my friend/colleague can recall with the wording, it went like this: You piece of shit. You haven't done anything for this neighborhood. You are a waste, a zero. I don't want you to talk to me and I will file a restraining order if you talk to me. We are talking about a neighborhood group leader. I think he owes this member of our community an apology!

Message: I first must say, I hope for a speedy recovery for these two badly injured policemen. On the night in question, I believe they were ambushed by a violent, armed, male. This male outgunned all who responded and by some miracle from powers above, the tactical car that carries the firepower to overcome such a person or persons, was close by East Boston, which in this case was far away from the city, location speaking as any other neighborhood. If by some remote chance that tactical car was at any other incident many lives would have been in grave danger. The mayor, city council, and your police comm all prior to this incident, informed the media, and union memberships that such firepower was not needed in Boston. Tell that to the poor families that are going through this tortuous ordeal they are now going through. Why are the unions quiet about this, why as a neighborhood are we quiet about this. Every police car absolutely should be equipped with a long rifle, time is very critical in these situations. But yet, nothing to see here folks. Reminds me of this election coverage. East Boston and the city of Boston were very close to a meltdown due to the inaction of politics as usual in this city and police department. God (truncated)

Last night's Orient Heights Neighborhood Council meeting should serve as a primer for corporations that want to circumvent established agreements in our community. Just remember to enlist the assistance of someone with poor recollection skills of what transpired during earlier meetings, e.g., gatherings of Impact Advisory Groups. The following is what key players did and, clearly, it worked. First, present your idea to the group assigned to the geographical boundaries where you will be doing business. Gauge the appetite for your proposal. If you sense that you do not have enough support, ask for a delay in a vote by the group. You may need to ask for several delays depending upon how long (probably months) it will take to gather enough people to attend the requisite number of meetings before they can cast votes. Then, you need to ask your "advocate" to find someone to speak favorably on your offering of cash to fix problems on private property that have been ignored by benign neglect. It won't matter if that speaker is from another municipality where he would never gain approval for a proposal such as yours (i.e., a large billboard.) It wouldn't hurt your argument to have another person lecture or preach to the group (truncated)
